description.value: Public or private space, that is open to the public on full open bases, or on bases of membership, without the need to consumation.

Sustainable mobility refers to the broad subject of transport that is sustainable in the senses of increased social benefit, combined with the significant reduction in environmental and climate impacts.

A bicycle repair shop, usually organized on volunteer bases, enabling and empowering people to self-repair their bikes. Often the repair shops are based on values of equality and are politically active for bicycling.
Awareness raising (some organizations also do lobbying) for better conditions for bicycling.

Sustainable energy production, that is owned by a collective form of ownership with a majority of individuals, where each individual holds a relatively small part of the investment and in some form relates to the location of the power plants.

Natural ressources, that are owned by a collective form of ownership with a majority of individuals, where each individual holds a relatively small part of the investment and in some form relates to the location of the ressource.
Forestland, that is owned and forested by a organized group of locals.

Cohousing is an intentional community of private homes clustered around shared space.

A commune is an intentional community of people living together, sharing common interests, often having common values and beliefs, as well as shared property, possessions, resources, and, in some communes, work and income and assets.
Ecovillages are intentional communities whose goal is to become more socially, economically and ecologically sustainable.

Fair trade is a social movement to help producers in developing countries achieve better trading conditions and to promote sustainability. Fair Trade advocates higher (just) prices, as well as improved social and environmental standards.

Compaines creating jobs for the disadvantaged - mentally, physically or else - and integrate them in the job market (ex-prisoners, drug-users, endangered teenagers, mathers after long maternity leave, people in the pre-retirement age ...).
Enterprise centres & incubators are spaces set up in communities to help people who are trying to start their own initiative (some whether profit or non-profit, some mainly profit oriented).
A Community currency is a type of complementary currency that is used by groups with a common bond, like members of a locality, or association. For example, a local currency is a community currency.
A community garden is a single piece of land gardened collectively by a group of people.
A group of people who organize to buy together directly from local producers.
A group of people who organize to buy together directly from local producers.

Guerrilla gardening is the act of gardening on land that the gardeners do not have the legal rights to utilize, such as an abandoned site, an area that is not being cared for, or private property. Often these projects get legal status granted.
Retail market featuring foods sold directly by local farmers to consumers.
Local farmers with weekly delivery service of fresh produce.
